Here's the full migration. Your code has three `Thread.Abort`-dependent patterns that all need different treatment in ASP.NET Core:

## Pattern Inventory

| Pattern | Location | ASP.NET Core Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | `btnExport_Click` | Remove — just return the result |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | `btnRedirect_Click` | Return `RedirectResult` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `btnRedirect_Click` | Remove entirely — no longer thrown |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8 / ASP.NET Core)

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;
using System.Text;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // Was: btnExport_Click with Response.Clear/Write/End
    [HttpPost("export")]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // Return a FileResult — the framework handles headers and content.
        // No Response.Clear/Write/End needed. Just return.
        return File(
            Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv"
        );
    }

    // Was: btnRedirect_Click with Response.Redirect(url, true)
    [HttpPost("process")]
    public IActionResult Process()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            // Redirect is now a return value, not a side-effect.
            // No Thread.Abort, no endResponse parameter.
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // ThreadAbortException catch is REMOVED — it is never thrown in .NET 8.
        // Thread.Abort throws PlatformNotSupportedException (SYSLIB0006).
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }

    private string GenerateReport() { /* ... */ }
    private void ProcessRequest() { /* ... */ }
    private void LogError(Exception ex) { /* ... */ }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls to Watch For

**1. `Response.End()` → just return**
In Web Forms, `Response.End()` called `Thread.Abort` to stop all execution after the write. In ASP.NET Core, returning an `IActionResult` ends the action naturally. Any code after `return` simply doesn't run — no abort needed.

**2. `Response.Redirect(url, true)` → `return Redirect(url)`**
The `true` (endResponse) parameter existed to abort the thread so no more code ran. In MVC/Core, `Redirect()` returns a result object — execution stops because you `return` it. Never call `HttpResponse.Redirect()` directly if you can return an `IActionResult`.

**3. Remove `catch (ThreadAbortException)` entirely**
This catch block was a Web Forms anti-pattern required because `Response.Redirect(url, true)` threw `ThreadAbortException` as a side-effect. In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (`SYSLIB0006`), and `ThreadAbortException` is never thrown. Leaving the catch block is dead code at best; at worst it hides a real bug if someone accidentally references `Thread.Abort`.

**4. Null-safety on `User.Identity`**
In ASP.NET Core, `User.Identity` can be `null` when no authentication middleware has run. Use `?.IsAuthenticated ?? true` or the `[Authorize]` attribute instead of manual checks.

**5. Long-running exports — use `HttpContext.RequestAborted`**
If `GenerateReport()` is slow, pass the cancellation token so the server stops work if the client disconnects:

```csharp
[HttpPost("export")]
public async Task<IActionResult> Export(CancellationToken cancellationToken)
{
    // ASP.NET Core binds this to HttpContext.RequestAborted automatically
    var data = await GenerateReportAsync(cancellationToken);
    return File(Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data), "text/csv", "report.csv");
}
```

This replaces the "abort the thread when the client disconnects" behavior that `Response.End()` approximated in Web Forms, but cooperatively.
